Let’s dissect this wonderfully archaic sentence. It’s a beautiful example of Early Modern English, deliberately employing a formal and somewhat elevated style. The core sentiment is one of familial duty and compassion, expressed with considerable flourish. Each word carries a weight of history and a deliberate formality – a stark contrast to modern speech. It’s a sentence designed to impress and evoke a sense of solemn responsibility. Consydre thou myne condicyon;

The sentence’s structure is complex, utilizing inversions and archaic phrasing. Notice the frequent use of “thou” and “thy,” reflecting the second-person singular pronoun system of the time. The repetition of “myne” emphasizes the speaker’s personal stake in the situation. The extended metaphor of the father’s suffering is central to the plea. Consydre thou myne condicyon;

The vocabulary itself is fascinating. “Strycken wyth blyndnesse” – struck with blindness – is a poetic way of describing illness or infirmity. “Destytute” and “penurye” highlight the father’s poverty and lack of resources. “Rendere hys latter yeeres” – render his latter years – is a formal way of saying to make his later years comfortable. Consydre thou myne condicyon;

The rhetorical question at the end – “Shall I forsake hym, when he is strycken wyth blyndnesse and destytute, to wrastle wyth infirmitie and penurye, when it lyeth wythin my poure to rendere hys latter yeeres fylled wyth comforte and joye?” – is a powerful appeal to conscience. It frames the decision as a moral imperative, weighing personal comfort against familial obligation. Consydre thou myne condicyon;

Overall, this sentence is a remarkable piece of writing, showcasing the elegance and formality of Early Modern English. It’s a testament to the power of language to convey complex emotions and moral dilemmas. Consydre thou myne condicyon;
